search:.NET Core + Entity Framework Logg.content:
- Install Serilog and EF Core logging packages via NuGet.
- Use `dotnet add package Serilog.AspNetCore` and `dotnet add package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore`.
- Configure Serilog in your `Program.cs` or `Startup.cs`:
  ```csharp
  var logger = new LoggerConfiguration()
      .ReadFrom.Configuration(configuration)
      .CreateLogger();

  Log.Logger = logger;
  ```
- Enable EF Core logging by configuring it in the `DbContext` constructor:
  ```csharp
  public MyDbContext(DbContextOptions<MyDbContext> options) : base(options)
  {
      ChangeTracker.QueryTrackingBehavior = QueryTrackingBehavior.NoTracking;
      ChangeTracker.AutoDetectChangesEnabled = false;
  }
  ```
- Use Serilog to log EF Core queries in your `Startup.cs`:
  ```csharp
  services.AddDbContext<MyDbContext>(options =>
      options.UseSqlServer(Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"))
             .LogTo(Console.WriteLine, LogLevel.Information));
  ```
- Ensure you have the necessary NuGet packages installed for Serilog and EF Core.
- Use `dotnet add package Serilog.Sinks.Console` for console logging.
- Configure Serilog in your `appsettings.json`:
  ```json
  "Serilog": {
    "Using": [ "Serilog.Sinks.Console" ],
    "MinimumLevel": { "Default": "Information", "Override": { "Microsoft": "Warning", "System": "Warning" } },
    "WriteTo": [ "Console" ]
  }
  ```
- Use `Log.Logger` to log messages throughout your application.
